Returns on effective giving wonâ€™t 3x in a day, and canâ€™t be bought & sold for a quick profit. Itâ€™s more of a @punk6529 philosophy - invest what youâ€™re able, keep learning, and see what happens in 2030.

Effective giving is one of the most important long-run investments we can make. My 2 largest investments in NFTs have been in @worldofwomennft & @crypto__chicks. A major factor for these investments was how strongly their teams are committed to working towards a better future.

On maximizing your impact: when we think of buying an NFT, we think *investment*, and try to pick the one thatâ€™s going to maximize utility ($, community, happiness, etc). But too often when we think of philanthropy, we donâ€™t think â€œinvestmentâ€, we think weâ€™re giving money away

The evidence is significant: giving cash is really effective. According to gold-standard charity evaluator GiveWell, GiveDirectly is one of the worldâ€™s leading organizations when it comes to maximizing your impact per dollar donated.

Just as NFTs liberate artists & creators from the limitations of traditional art constructs, @GiveDirectly frees recipients of aid from the restrictions of traditional philanthropy. In both cases, power shifts into the hands of those most deserving of it.

A powerful effect of giving unconditional cash is that it eliminates the implication baked into traditional philanthropy that donors & staff (despite good intentions) have a better sense of what's best for recipients than the recipients themselves.

Iâ€™ve posted it before, but itâ€™s important to recap why giving cash is so empowering: 

People living in poverty rarely get the chance to have any say over how money intended to help them gets spent. GiveDirectly offers recipients the freedom to make their own financial choices.
